			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">[quote]Wouldn't it be better if they were given some -other- way to gain mana, that doesn't go against the point of the spells? [/quote]
<br />

<br />
I'm trying to look at the big picture.  Mages having a way to gain mana back faster doesn't hurt me.  In fact, during a raid, it even helps.  If it helps to burn down the named a bit faster, where is that harm?
<br />

<br />
On the other hand, when the mage can get so much mana from doing this that they don't even send their pet in to attack, there is a problem.  This needs to be adjusted so that there is more benefit to having a pet meleeing the named does more damage than continually summoning/reclaiming it.
<br />

<br />
Until recently, with luclin AA's and especially the time pet focus item (that gave the pet a large HP boost, and thus, allowed the mana reclaimed from the pet to be so much more than the mana spent to cast it), this was mostly the case - the mana gained from pet canni and nuking was about the same as if the mage was nuking more moderately and having the pet attack.  And most mages didn't bother doing it.
<br />

<br />
Between pulls in a group, or when soloing - or even between named pulls in a raid, it is nice that mages have a unique way to speed up med.  What is the point of taking this away, only to partially replace it with another self only mana buff, like every other class has?
<br />

<br />
This just need to be adjusted so that it is *only* a benefit to refill mana during downtime, and isn't worth it to actually use *during* the fight.  It is kind of silly to see a mage basically taking over the wizard's role, chain nuking and using a pet only to regain mana.
<br />

<br />
It should always be better for a mage to send the pet in and attack, than to chain nuke without a pet.  During downtime, if there is a way for them to fill up the blue bar a little faster, where is the harm?
<br />

<br />
-Kryq</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
